    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i was reading about hiit workouts and it mentioned lactic acid. can u explain how it actually gets made in the muscles when u go hard and how the body gets rid of it afterwards?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "High-intensity interval training (HIIT) pushes your muscles to work harder than usual, causing them to produce lactic acid. Lactic acid is a byproduct of the anaerobic breakdown of glucose for energy when there isn't enough oxygen, like during intense exercise. Your body eventually starts to break down and clear the lactic acid through the Cori Cycle and by re-oxygenating your muscles during the rest periods between exercise intervals. This process helps to diminish the uncomfortable feeling in your muscles, commonly known as muscle fatigue.",
      "source": "target",
